 revivalism in this period framed the rules and identities of the expanding market economy and the national policy. "Subtle and complex. . . . Fascinating."—Randolph Roth, Pennsylvania History "[Revivalism and Cultural Change] should be read with interest by those interested in religious movements as well as the connections among religion, economics, and politics."—Charles L. Harper, Contemporary Sociology "Readers old and new stand to gain much from Thomas's sophisticated study of the macrosociology of religion in the United States during the nineteenth century. . . . He has given the sociology of religion its best quantitative study of revivalism since the close of the 1970s."—Journal for the Scientific Study of Religion  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aChristian sociologyzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aChristianity and culturexHistoryy19th century. 0aPolitics and government. 0aRevivalszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  areligion, christianity, revivalism, secularism, spirituality, commerce, capitalism, nation, sociology, history, evangelism, republicanism, expansion, social movements, economics, politics, republican party, revivals, gnosticism, state formation, polity, ontology, reason, rationality, individualism, individuation, protestantism, power, affinity, elections, electorate, voters, nonfiction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1960-1989z978311066784440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226924786423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226924786/original  a978-3-11-066784-4  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1960-1989c1960d1989  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles